   <mods:abstract>John Jay is glad that the decrease in legislative business permits him
            leisure to attend to his friends. He was happy to meet Mr. Wentworth, whose deportment
            and manner are attractive, but was even more pleased because he carried a letter from
            Mrs. Morton. As for the gentleman mentioned in Mrs. Morton's letter, his "real character
            and object... are unknown to me: In Times like these it is not always easy to learn or
            discern the character and views of Travelers." John Jay finds this spring "a delightful
            Season, and tho' more than twice five and twenty, I enjoy it." John Jay hopes that the
            fine weather may prompt Mrs. Morton's muse to more of the effusions which have so
            charmed her friends. Mrs. Jay has been unwell for nearly a year, but she has been
            feeling better in the past weeks.</mods:abstract>
